                  <msContents>
                     <msItem class="#liturgica" n="1" xml:id="MS_Selden_Supra_43-part2-item1">
                        <locus from="98">(fol. 98)</locus>
                        <title key="work_13657" type="desc">Ordinal (Pye), Use of Sarum</title>
                        <note>Not quoted among the known MSS. by canon Chr. Wordsworth, Ordinale Sarum, H. B. S., vol. xx (1901). Incorporates a version of <persName role="aut" key="person_5167">Thomas Grantham</persName>, <title key="work_7534">Regula de omnibus historiis inchoandis</title>, for which see Sharpe, <title>Latin Writers</title> </note>
                        <finalRubric><locus>(fol. 150v-151r)</locus> Explicit compendiosus tractatus de historiis inchoandis ... per deuotum virum dominum Thomam Grantham | dudum vicarium in capella regia infra palacium Westmon' utiliter compilatus ... Predictus tamen tractatus per alium est transpositus et locatus secundum cursum anni et ordinem historiarum ita videlict quod qualibet historia per seipsum integre collocatur</finalRubric>
                        <note>De inceptione historie Aspiciens ubi fiunt due commemorationes per ebdomadam (fol. 98); Noticia regule de inchoatione et duracione historiarum Domine ne in ira et Deus omnium et de omnibus responsuriis ferialibus cantandis, missis dominicalibus dicendis et de commemorationibus faciendis (fol. 101); Deus omnium (fol. 130); de inceptione aliarum historiarum per estatem ubi fiunt due commemorationes (fol. 144v); the whole being ascribed (fol. 150v f.) to Thomas Grantham vicarius in capella regia infra palacium Westmonasteriense. Then follow De inceptione eiusdem historie [Deus omnium] during the octave of Corpus Christi (fol. 151) and a shortened and different version of Thomas Grantham’s treatise (fol. 155), made with the aid of the existing pyes.</note>
                        <textLang mainLang="la">Latin</textLang>
                     </msItem>
                  </msContents>
